Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comical, the assiduous effort with which Barack Obama, president with a reputation for wisdom, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered very simple.
When he finally let his long-awaited doctrine perspire, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper since Bush’s Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content with using in the text even several times the expression "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a war-torn Iraq as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers at present do not speak at all about Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, however, objectively speaking, it left his successor in a final situation much more favorable than one could have hoped for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the reticence of the White House despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least swindled the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to extirpate the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally counted on 10,000.
What brings the most problems to Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. The whole Obama doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a halved increase will bring the same benefits as progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out in exactly the opposite way - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
In these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders day by day according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only a powder keg behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is singularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups given the lack of clarity about the relationships, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a “state ready to act,” which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is perplexing by its voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the verge of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out-of-reality heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war with a view to their "prompt return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will regard it as the indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the Europeans' willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving in the negative direction.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves facing the very difficult issue of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution would lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only dent for Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential election and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
