Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Pneumococcal vaccination will reverse old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
There are already voices saying that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are peaking.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines the maximum prices that health insurance will pay for vaccines.
Specialists also see clearly in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccinations for children in August.
Since January, children born last year from August 2 can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started the vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of vaccine should be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Already last year, a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococci.
Yet parents paid 1,600 kroner or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Experts estimate that every year health insurance spends 300-450,000 kroner on vaccine doses.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
Until now the state spent about 500,000 kroner a year on all vaccinations of children.
The reimbursed vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococci are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the meninges and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under the age of 10 caused by pneumococcal infections.
Aside from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced the reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions regarding a possible vaccination obligation in the future.
From January, it must be paid by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD> indicated that a mandatory vaccination would be more positive.
Her association has long promoted pneumococcal vaccination.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to have been able to impose at least this.
I think that this is a direction that must now be followed, Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD> said.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the process of vaccination against pneumococci.
We are absolutely not considering it at the moment, said its spokesman Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Society of Pediatricians, acknowledges that a vaccination based on voluntariata its shortcomings.
"In the situation where the vaccine costs so much, I understand the decision to make the vaccination optional," Cabrnochová said.
Experts predict that as early as next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
The pneumococcal vaccination also marks a break from the fact that it is the first vaccination of children that is funded by insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance should free up funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their own products
This is, however, related to the concerns of practicing pediatricians, which relate to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intention was to have the vaccines purchased by insurance companies, with doctors receiving them in the same way as other vaccine products provided by the state.
Some MEPs feared, however, that this would allow insurance companies to "deduct sums from health insurance".
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to reimburse them.
It is estimated that individual pediatricians will have to invest nearly 40,000 kroner per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
