The Labour Party is calling for an increase in the budget tax.
Ministers defended the tax increase and spending cuts announced in the pre-Budget report, despite criticism from the opposition, businesses and unions.
The Tories claimed that Alistair Darling "missed" an opportunity to show he was serious about reducing the deficit by postponing his decisions until after the election.
The Chancellor also took the heat by attacking low and average salaries.
Among its main proposals, we can see an increase of 0.5% in Social Insurance and a ceiling rate of 1% on public wages from 2011.
The Anger of Social Security
The unions have protested that low wages are being penalized by a recession for which they are not responsible and have warned that there are “problems” ahead.
The reduction in Social Insurance - which will get about 3 billion GBP a year - has angered the business world, because according to him, it is a tax on jobs while the goal should be a revival of the economy.
The increase, reserved for those earning more than <0xC2><0xA3>20,000 a year, will affect around 10 million workers.
KEY POINTS OF THE PRE-BUDGET REPORT
Social Insurance will increase by 0.5% from April 2011
The economy will decline even more than the 4.75% expected this year
New 50% Tax on Bankers’ Bonuses
The increase in corporation tax on profits for small companies has been abandoned
Tax rebates for electric cars and wind turbines
Increase in pensions by 2.5%
According to Treasury estimates, a person earning <0xC2><0xA3>30,000 will lose <0xC2><0xA3>90 a year and a person earning <0xC2><0xA3>40,000 will lose <0xC2><0xA3>190, while a person earning <0xC2><0xA3>10,000 a year will earn <0xC2><0xA3>110 more.
The ministers said their goal of halving the deficit by 2013 was leading to "difficult decisions" but insisted that 60 percent of the additional tax burden would be borne by the top 5 percent of employees.
Stephen Timms, the Treasury Secretary, refuted an increase in the tax and pointed out that a decrease in spending was a “drop in the ocean” compared to what was needed.
"These figures are important, they will allow us to halve the deficit, which will be absolutely essential over the next four years," he told the BBC.
Timms said he was confident the economy would grow again by the end of the year.
However, Labour’s forecasts for economic growth – which will influence how much it will have to borrow and how quickly the deficit will be filled – have been called into question after the Chancellor was forced to revise his first figures.
In his speech, he said the economy would likely decline by 4.75% this year – far worse than the 3.5% decline predicted in April – while borrowing would be 3 billion GDP higher than the previous estimate.
'Opportunity missed'
The Conservatives, who will launch a new advertising campaign warning against Labour's "debt crisis" on Thursday, said the plan to borrow <0xC2><0xA3>789bn over the next six years was not viable.
Ministers failed to come up with a credible plan on how to repay, they added, “cynically” eluding difficult choices until after the elections – which are due to be held in June 2010.
"They didn't present anything significant about what they were going to do," said Philip Hammond, the Shadow Chief of Staff's Treasury. "They had the opportunity to do it and they missed it."
“Important announcements will be made after the election, regardless of the winner.”
by Roger Bootle, Deloitte
Labour insists that schools, hospitals and the police will be protected from future cuts, contrary to the Tory proposals that would lead to a faster and larger reduction in the deficit.
But the Lib Dems claimed that the money raised through higher taxes and lower spending would be used to support next year’s spending and not to reduce the deficit, arguing that the plans were “built on wind”.
Nick Robinson, the BBC's political editor, claimed that the timing of announcements - such as the above-mentioned rise in inflation for certain disability benefits next April - would leave the Chancellor facing propaganda charges, with the money simply being recovered the following year.
However, Labour insists that more help is being provided when people need it most and that the situation will be reviewed in September 2010.
"False Budget"
Although ministers did not release details of spending beyond 2011, economists said it was clear that restrictions on public spending would only begin to be felt in the medium term.
The highly respected Institute for Fiscal Studies said the Chancellor's figures imply, in the future, substantial reductions in many areas, potentially including transport, higher education, science and defence.
“The pain is actually just postponed,” said Director Robert Chote.
“The most important announcements will be made after the election, regardless of the winner,” said Roger Bootle, economic adviser to Deloitte’s accountants.
"This was a false pre-budget report. The markets are well aware of it."
