Amnesty condemns Iranian "abuses"
Over the past two decades, human rights have been as under-achieved as ever, according to Amnesty International’s report.
the report presents "repetitions of violations" by the regime, before and after the presidential election campaign in June.
One man cited in the report claimed he had been beaten and burned with cigarettes. Another said he had been threatened with rape.
Iran has denied previous criticism of its failure to respect human rights.
The authorities have claimed that such criticism is politically motivated.
Thousands have been arrested and dozens killed in Iran after the disputed election of President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad led to the largest public demonstrations since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
Dozens have been sentenced to prison terms and prosecutors say at least five people have been sentenced to death.
Jon Leyne, BBC correspondent in Tehran, now in London, says that at the start of the protests, Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei acknowledged some of the allegations of abuse, ordering the closure of the Kahrizak detention centre.
But since then, the authorities have not tolerated any criticism, says our correspondent.
"False confession"
Amnesty International has documented the case of a 26-year-old computer science student, Ebrahim Mehtari, who said he was accused of “working with Facebook networks” and protesting against the election results.
“They often hit me in the face,” he was quoted as saying.
“I was burned with cigarettes, under the eyes, on the neck, on the head... They threatened to execute me and humiliated me.”
After five days, he signed a false confession and was released and left on the street, still in blood and half-conscious, Amnesty said.
In August, the losing candidate in the elections, Mehdi Karroubi, claimed that protesters detained after the election were tortured to death in prison and that others were raped.
