It gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Washington representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what U.N. Executive Secretary-General on climate change Yvo de Boer described as the “full picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020 by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, the U.S. climate negotiator, rejected any discussion that would force industrialized countries to cut greenhouse gases, compared with voluntary efforts by major emerging economies if they were not funded by developed countries.
