The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions by major developing countries, Stern said, also regretting that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said the US chief negotiator either lacked “common sense” or was “extremely irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the US would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than rescuing the planet, with China and the United States quarreling over their respective obligations as poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the costs of cutting greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold major emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of those countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change said they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most major participants said negotiations would lead to a political agreement at a minimum.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission's climate unit, said that the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the entire political process", in part by what they are now unified and calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the outstanding issues before heads of government could reach agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Environment Minister, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Vice-Minister got off their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and briefings, so that they could make claims that will be investigated over the next week.
