The managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to determined "values" from above as it was formerly, to impose on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets back where they belong... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are disconnected from customer preference factors comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, even more so, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that the revenues of authoritarian management totally contradict.
This is why we call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the center of the company’s concerns on the same level as the customer.
The Relative Utility of Internal Opinion Surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire Orange submitted to its employees – incite this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First because I could see that, faced with a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do first... what it has always done.!
- Then, because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and Measuring Mobilization Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to achieve part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motive Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can monitor, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resource management “on the spot.”
They thus create a favorable terrain for the concerted development of a robust and efficient economic intelligence.
