The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa ellae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended in sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have had anything exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the land surface of the supercontinent, the Pangaea, and was located near the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Triassic.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have uncovered the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and limited to a few fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it allows to confirm some theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians divided into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaur and the velociraptor appeared later and from which the birds descend, the sauropods, quadrupeds with long necks, and those that are related to them and the herbivores ornithischians of which are part.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the earliest theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues suggesting that Tawa hablae had small air sacs in its bones at the level of the skull, just like the birds that are the descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that the vertebrae of the Tawa hallae have also been partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed air sacs and a light frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, researchers concluded that saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three great lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, the whole of the land that formed the supercontinent Pangaea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot be descended from a common ancestor that has migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the Natural History Museum in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are of course some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silesaurus, that lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give an erroneous view because there are in South America a large number of dinosaur fossils that have been preserved while practically none are found on other continents.
However, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapod of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread all over the planet, favoring the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction in which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate the competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the development of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and which since that time vegetated in the shade: they were mammals.
