However, the one who, awake, experiences the dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world to be crazy or drugged, or at least to be an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the mentally ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but which sometimes incites the limits between dream, madness and reality to blend in.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, at best it is called visions, at worst madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect stand out, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance of the brain’s neurotransmitters – first and foremost dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achetylcholine – breaks down and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts often occur during a schizophrenic psychosis.
The force of attraction of the earth no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always focused on the relationship between madness and dream.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of daydreaming; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
It’s the fall of 2001 when Henning T transforms into a comic book character.
Its body is in two dimensions with garish colors.
The terrestrial attraction no longer has power over him, he hovers at the raz of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him are winged, grimacing devil creatures, their mouths bleeding, showing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flamboyant boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Loud, wicked voices, screaming, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. rips two cables from his stereo, loops them and attaches them to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and loops around his neck.
He jumps.
The loop comes off.
Let it be a lesson to you, shout the voices in a choir to rip out the eardrum. "Go to a clinic and get treated!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last date of 2 years, the first of almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizo-affective psychosis, paranoid, in addition he is manic-depressive, he takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despairs.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers at least once in their lifetime from schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, the people concerned can no longer tell the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper arousal, which causes them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned under the sensations.
Like dreams, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of psychiatry at the Heidelberg University Hospital (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universit<0xC3><0xA4>tsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is at the center of the situation, all with a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the possibility to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experience once in your life a hallucination.
In contrast to dreaming, according to Fuchs, “the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis is fundamentally conserved.”
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience takes place in a real setting.
Why our brains do these kinds of stunts is still an enigma to researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to momentarily lose the perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
The researchers assume that the people involved have very small brain damage.
It is assumed that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development by, for example, a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But what still remains unexplained is the way in which the neuronal system anomaly occurs and the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is any predisposition.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain heats up.
What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of L<0xC3><0xBC>beck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy very expensive drugs to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been compiling reports on hallucinations and the phenomena of illusory images for the past ten years: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also of an impressive number of other pathologies.
These include psychological disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
It is surprising to find that in certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions, are overactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain heats up but also when there is a lack of stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this state just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimuli, stress, love griefs or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, a third of participants admit to having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in former Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and she goes to high school.
A girl doing everything normal, really.
If there were no images and voices.
During recess, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long brown hair, speaks to him.
When she answers, her classmates look at her in amazement – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a whimsical dreamer but Sarah K does not dream, she is certain of it.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
It can even perceive its presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she finds this young man friendly.
Am I crazy? she asks herself sometimes.
But she knows well that this young man and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
Often the visions are heavy.
When she is in class, she may not be able to take the class because the teacher is just presenting a new student in her eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is visibly explaining equations on the board.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for the sleep that comes too rarely and far too late, she can often not make the distinction whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees, the grimacing faces or the girl with bloody nicks on her arms and legs are before her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she cries out to these creatures.
She doesn't talk about it to her parents or her friends, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She got her bachelor's degree last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she came into contact with the psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the likelihood is high that they will hallucinate after a while.
I guess the brain's not busy enough, so there's animation.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played by herself.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at age 13 that the man she called dad, since she was of age to think, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to tell the difference between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten "takes place in the brain, reality is formed from there.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those in acute psychoses.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
This is why Kasten advises his patients to treasure hallucinations as a special talent.
There is only one step between the dream and the hallucination.
In our overly consciousness-centered world, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at Florence Nightingale Hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease that also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of the dream-awakened modification of consciousness.
The oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the person who lives them and that he can not differentiate from the dream even when he is in a state of awakening.
The state of oniroid consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and of the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that undermines his life, by his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation in itself intolerable, an organizational capacity that is given to us men, not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his dreamlike experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as a saving action of the soul.
He is 49 years old, when his conscious goes on a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen dives into a world he created from scratch, visiting foreign places, time travel. He sees himself as an old man in bed in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lived in the Middle Ages among nobles who manufactured blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcycle who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He absorbs himself completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes describing what he experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In short, oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be very rewarding.
