The promise of FonPeek
Peek is extremely limited, it is a device that only allows you to look at your email, without offering the possibility of even seeing certain types of attachments or browsing the Internet.
He enjoyed his five minutes of fame in the United States, when Time magazine named him one of the products of the year.
In truth, it is more difficult to see it on the street, but the idea seems interesting, especially for young people.
Unlike smartphones, Peek offers a very low price and a monthly subscription, which is less than half of what it costs, for example, the data subscription of the iPhone.
Given its success, the company has launched two new devices: one designed exclusively for Twitter, the other with a free lifetime data service, for six times more expensive than the Peek.
FonPeek, presented yesterday at the event The Web, is the European version of the invention and its third incarnation.
He is just as limited as his American big brother, but comes with a surprise.
The price of its monthly subscription, around 12 euros, includes roaming throughout Europe.
Those who travel with a Smartphone already know what it means to give up data when crossing a border or desperately looking for a cafeteria on the Wifi (or a Fon connection) to be able to consult his mail.
The idea of roaming at a fixed price is incredibly appealing and has long been expected to work.
Indeed, some operators have special agreements and travel options, but as far as I am concerned, I would need to have done a thesis in physics to understand them and good glasses to read small print.
The European Commission's repeated calls for affordable roaming rates across Europe have had a barely noticeable effect.
Outside of your home country, you're hesitant to use the data, and you're not wrong.
That a small device like the FonPeek (it is always curious that it is called Fon when it does not have Wifi) offers this type of rates, means that operators begin to think differently and study different proposals allowing them to make their data network profitable.
Kindle is another good example, it includes downloading books and other research on the Internet.
No subscription and no hassle.
It is a connected device and you pay when you buy it and not every month.
And this is what I hope to see one day for the FonPeek: a purchase option with lifetime access as Peek already offers in the United States.
Not that I want to buy it.
I'm looking at my mail on my phone, thank you.
I just want it because I believe it is a fairer formula for the consumer.
It would be interesting to see a computer with the same system.
