75% of working mothers have had work-related problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fecundity and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their professional career limited because of motherhood.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of job occupied.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, postpone entry into couple life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with stable employment have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of common life, "explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 and 32.1 years, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed basic education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child, "says Ms. Delgado.
