After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market is starting to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decrease, according to the figures of the employers' union of manufacturers Anfac and Ganvam, that of dealers.
However, the good news needs to be nuanced, since the reference for comparison, November 2008, was particularly bad, with a 60% decrease compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite the rebound of last month, the registrations accumulated in these 11 months are 40% below those of the previous year.
Since January, if we add up all the vehicles that fall into the category of light commercial vehicles (derived from passenger cars, pick-ups, vans, light vans and light chassis trucks) 95 853 have been sold.
The big clouds that affect their demand the most have not dissipated, because although they are also purchased by individuals, most purchases are made by small or medium-sized companies, which pay in almost 100% of cases through external financing.
Thus, in addition to the restrictions implied by the limitation of bank credits, other factors must be added, such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
In the face of this situation and unlike the passenger vehicles, the 2000E purchase aid was of little use.
In addition to individuals, the self-employed and SMEs who wish to acquire a light commercial vehicle of less than 3.5 tonnes with a level of CO2 emissions that does not exceed 160 grams per kilometre, can also benefit, but the number of operations speaks for itself.
