Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as will be the case with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory feature on European cars.
They are already mandatory on passenger cars and light commercial vehicles newly registered, while for the rest of the vehicles a grace period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The Emergency Brake Assist works by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver’s kick.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the car parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken advantage of its full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revenge, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with these elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is calculated that one in four accidents with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to slightly acting on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum force on the brakes to minimize damage.
