After rosy days since last spring, during which asset inflation has been the dominant note in the markets, uncertainty is emerging again, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment where agents make decisions about a future that is inherently uncertain.
The remedy employed by central banks to stabilize markets has been to monetize debt through the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving abundant liquidity at near-zero rates, so that financial institutions buy assets to be mobilized.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been virtually finalized and, without questioning their non-conformist liquidity policy, are starting to put some sand in the wheels, as the ECB has done, with their auction one year from next week.
Therefore, investors doubt the ability of the global economy to sustain an economic recovery without heterodox measures and we are witnessing a reversal of the reduction in risk premiums.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are rising again, although they remain far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
States have been forced to socialize private risk and public debt is again affected.
There is again a flight to quality and the United States, Japan and Germany have been the refuges chosen by investors, causing an increase in the differences between the countries of the euro zone and Germany.
Spain was barely affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor's threatened a further downward revision of the qualification of the Kingdom of Spain.
